Organization: Northwestern University, Evanston Illinois.
Lines: 593

Here is the first of 10 commented Dang Hu Games I am going to post.  As I
mentioned, each game will be dedicated to a person that has helped me to
improve my Go and that has inspired me to do this work.  I wish I can do
more than 10 games since people I want to thank are definitely more than
10. (BTW, I might not reveal this person's real name, since I might have
never seen him before, but only get to know each other through IGS -- so, I
will use his name on IGS if possible.)

This first game is dedicated to *jansteen 3d*, who has posted quite a few
games here (Honinbo, Tengen, etc.).  What I am doing is nothing but to
follow his footstep.

-jzy NR ^_^


(
;
GaMe[1]
VieW[]
SiZe[19]
AddWhite[dd][pp]
AddBlack[dp][pd]
Comment[Game 1

White: Shi Xiang-Xia

Black: Fan Xi-Ping

Date: 1739   Place: Dang Hu


Four stones are placed on the board \(as shown\) before the first move \(white\).  They are called "seated stones."  Because of these "seated stones," the opening of ancient Chinese games were rather simple and dull.  However, the midgame fights became extremely violent, and ancient Chinese players were good at fighting.]
;
White[qf]
;
Black[qk]
Comment[A move hardly seen in modern games.  It's hard to understand why B would allow enough space for W to play R11.  Apparently, ancient Chinese players were confident of their fighting strength.]
;
